In her first study, Dr. Levy tested the memories of 90 healthy older people. Then she flashed positive words about aging like ''guidance,'' ''wise,'' ''alert,'' ''sage'' and ''learned'' and tested them again. Their memories were better and they even walked faster. Next, she flashed negative words like ''dementia,'' ''decline,'' ''senile,'' ''confused'' and ''decrepit.'' This time, her subjects' memories were worse, and their walking paces slowed. Thomas Hess, a psychology professor at North Carolina State University, came to a similar conclusion about the effects of stereotypes of aging. In his studies, older people did significantly worse on memory tests if they were first told something that would bring to mind aging stereotypes. It could be as simple as saying the study was on how aging affects learning and memory. They did better on memory tests if Dr. Hess first told them something positive, like saying that there was not much of a decline in memory with age.
